    <abstract><!-- can be changed via merge in the assembly -->
      <para>
        NetworkManager enables managing network connections and you can interact with NetworkManager using <command>nmcli</command>. The <literal>journald</literal> system logging mechanism is used to record the activities. The NetworkManager logs are saved in <filename>/var/log/syslog</filename> and you can access the details using the <command>journalctl</command> command.</para>
       </abstract>
  </info>
<procedure xml:id="manage-networkmanager-logs"><title>Managing NetworkManager logs</title>
<para>The NetworkManager logs are available in the following debug levels:</para>
<itemizedlist>
  <listitem>
    <para><emphasis>ERR</emphasis> logs only error messages.</para>
  </listitem>
  <listitem>
    <para><emphasis>WARN</emphasis> logs warnings and errors.</para>
  </listitem>
  <listitem>
    <para><emphasis>INFO</emphasis> logs informational messsages.</para>
  </listitem>
  <listitem>
    <para><emphasis>DEBUG</emphasis> logs detailed debugging information.</para>
  </listitem>
</itemizedlist>
    <step><para>To view the current logging level:</para>
      <screen>nmcli general logging</screen>
      </step>
      <step><para>To configure the new logging level:</para>
       <screen>nmcli general logging level <replaceable>LEVEL</replaceable> domains <replaceable>DOMAINS</replaceable></screen>
       <para>Replace <replaceable>LEVEL</replaceable> with one of the debug levels such as ERR, WARN, INFO or DEBUG and replace <replaceable>DOMAINS</replaceable> with one or more domain categories. To enable detailed debugging for all domains, run the command <command>nmcli general logging level DEBUG domains ALL</command> command.
   </para>
   </step>
   <step><para>To revert the &nm; logging to default:</para>
   <screen>nmcli general logging level INFO domains NONE</screen></step>
   </procedure>
   <procedure xml:id="view-networkmanager-logs"><title>Viewing &nm; logs</title>
    <step><para>To view the &nm; logs:</para>
      <screen>journalctl -u NetworkManager</screen>
      </step>
      <step><para>To view the real-time &nm; logsd:</para>
      <screen>journalctl -u NetworkManager -f</screen>
      </step>
      <step><para>To view specific logs, such as logs related to DHCP:</para>
      <screen>journalctl -u NetworkManager | grep DHCP</screen>
      </step>
      <step><para>To save &nm; logs to <filename>networkmanager.log</filename> file:</para>
      <screen>journalctl -u NetworkManager > networkmanager.log</screen>
      </step>
      <step><para>To save the &nm; logs of a specific time to <filename>networkmanager_timerange.log</filename> file:</para>
      <screen>journalctl -u NetworkManager --since "<replaceable>YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS</replaceable>" --until "<replaceable>YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS</replaceable>" > networkmanager_timerange.log
</screen>
      </step>
      <step><para>To save the &nm; logs with real-time monitoring and save them as and when generated:</para>
      <screen>journalctl -u NetworkManager -f > <filename>live_networkmanager.log</filename>
</screen><para>The logs are saved in </para>
      </step>
   </procedure>
